<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE STATE; 
</P>
<P>
SCHOOLS HOPE TO RAISE SCORES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Los Angeles Board of Education today will consider a 10-year, $431-million 
plan aimed at reversing academic failure, particularly among poor, minority 
students. The plan incorporates many ideas that school districts are 
increasingly adopting to fight chronically poor test scores and high dropout 
rates. Programs emphasize smaller classes and strong early education, as well 
as ways to restructure school management, shifting authority to individual 
schools and to teachers. With the board deliberating over $90 million in budget 
cuts that district officials say are needed to pay higher teacher salaries, the 
steep price of the plan is likely to prompt concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES UNIFIED SCHOOL DISTRICT; SCHOOLS -- FINANCES; DROPOUTS; EDUCATION 
REFORM; LOS ANGELES BOARD OF EDUCATION; MINORITIES -- EDUCATION; LOS ANGELES -- 
SCHOOLS; PROFICIENCY TESTS; GRADES (EDUCATION) 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
